 the population—from very young children to the elderly—with far-reaching and often devastating consequences. Cruel but Not Unusual draws on the expertise of scholars and practitioners to present readers with the latest research and thinking about the history, conditions, and impact of violence in these contexts. For this new edition, chapters have been updated to reflect changes in data and legislation. New chapters include an examination of trauma from a neurobiological perspective; a critical analysis of the “gender symmetry debate,” a debate that questions the gendered nature of intimate violence; and an essay on the history and evolution of the women’s movement dedicated to addressing violence against women, which advances theoretical developments that remind readers of the breadth of inclusivity that should be at the heart of working in this field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbused older peoplezCanada. 0aChildren and violence - Canada. 0aChildren and violencezCanada. 0aFamily violencezCanada. 0aFamily violence--Canada. 0aWomenxViolence againstzCanada. 4aFamily & Relationships: Child Abuse. 4aFamily & Relationships: Domestic Violence. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Abuse / Child Abuse.2bisacsh1 aAlaggia, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlaggia, Ramona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaskin, Cyndy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirnbaum, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, April, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDergal, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Shain